annotation:
“Eyes Open” is one of two songs Taylor wrote for the soundtrack of the first Hunger Games movie, but it is not included in the film. The song appears to be about Katniss’s relationship with the Capitol, and serves as a warning for her not to trust anyone.
Taylor teased the song at a concert in Auckland prior to its release, performing it on an acoustic guitar to give fans a feel for the track. It debuted on Billboard Top 100 at number 19 and was received with general critical acclaim from contemporary critics.

annotation:
“Style” details a tumultuous relationship between two people who keep coming back to each other. Swift seems to have taken inspiration from her romance with Harry Styles, even referencing some of his band’s music.
Swift teased lyrics from a song in a since-deleted Instagram post from October 2014. She released it as the album’s third single in February 2015, following “Shake It Off” and “Blank Space,” along with a music video starring Dominic Sherwood.
As of December 2015, RIAA has certified the song triple platinum, with over three million units sold in the United States, and it’s also been certified triple platinum in Canada. It’s also double platinum in Australia, gold in New Zealand, and gold in the United Kingdom.
Swift’s friend Lorde shared via Twitter that this is her favorite song on 1989.

annotation:
“Out Of The Woods” captures the anxiety and excitement of a past relationship that Taylor treasures the memories of. It was the second promo single released from 1989, and later became the sixth official single. It was co-written by Jack Antonoff of Fun. and Bleachers, who worked on many songs for the album, and later joined Taylor to create her 2017 album reputation. It is known that she was writing to track for this song, something she was not used to at the time.
A short preview of the song was shown on Good Morning America on October 13th, 2014, and the full version was released the next day. The song’s music video was premiered on December 31st, 2015, during ABC’s annual Dick Clark’s New Year’s Rockin' Eve broadcast.
The song’s hidden message is, “They loved each other recklessly.”
The blue dress that Taylor Swift wore in the music video made a return at the beginning of the 2017 “Look What You Made Me Do” music video:

“Hits Different” was a bonus track on the Target-exclusive Midnights: Lavender Edition. However, due to requests from fans, Taylor announced on May 24, 2023 that the track would be included on Midnights (Til Dawn Edition) which released on May 26, 2023 on streaming platforms.
This track describes Taylor in a state of heartbreak that she has previously not experienced. It “hits different”, that is, it is out of the ordinary.
While Taylor has previously shunned lovers who left her such as in “White Horse” and “Picture to Burn”, here, Taylor describes a situation of struggling to move on and wanting an ex back, similar to “Death by a Thousand Cuts”.

annotation:
A cut from Taylor Swift’s 2012 Red album, “Better Man” captures the feeling of getting out of a toxic, perhaps abusive, relationship and accepting the sorrow that follows the breakup.
“Better Man” was Swift’s first country track in over two years — she crossed over to pop with her 2014 record 1989. She later gave another Red reject, “Babe,” to Sugarland, and recorded her own renditions of both songs on her 2021 Red (Taylor’s Version) project.
The song won a Grammy for “Best Country Duo/Group Performance” at the 2018 Grammy Awards.

annotation:
“Renegade” describes being with someone who deals with mental health issues, while expressing both sympathy and frustration for how it affects the relationship. Fans believe it may take inspiration from Swift’s relationship with Joe Alwyn, who stayed by her side through the mental health battles she describes on songs like “The Archer.”
“Renegade” is one of two Taylor Swift collaborations on How Long Do You Think It’s Gonna Last?, along with “Birch,” both of which she helped co-write. As reported by Secretly Store, Swift recorded her vocals while quarantining with Aaron Dessner ahead of the 2021 Grammys, where Swift and Dessner won the Album of the Year accolade for folklore.
This isn’t the first time Taylor and Justin Vernon have vocals on the same track, with them both also featuring on four of Swift’s 2020 Dessner produced tracks (They duetted on exile and evermore, whilst Vernon also provided backing vocals for her tracks ivy and marjorie).

annotation:
“Sweet Nothing,” the twelfth track on Midnights, is a slow, soft love song which seems to reflect the concept of soft words exchanged between lovers that are often called “sweet nothings”. The song follows Taylor’s simple gratitude and love of the life that she has built with boyfriend Joe Alwyn. Swift speaks of how she finds peace in her romantic relationship with her partner who asks “sweet nothing” of her as opposed to the pressures she faces from the media, a topic Swift has written about frequently, namely in her 2017 album reputation and the Midnights lead single “Anti-Hero”.
The song is written by Taylor Swift and Joe Alwyn under the alias, William Bowery. This is not the first time that Alwyn/Bowery has been featured as a writer on one of Swift’s tracks. Bowery has writing credits on folklore’s track 4, “exile”, and track 14 “betty”, and evermore’s “champagne problems”, “coney island”, and the titular closing track “evermore”.
